Comment: So, I often use this opening :D
Tawba's response is e5, which always make me attack that piece, so...
I think a lot of people would play Nc6, but I didn't meet it now.
I brought my bishop to c4 attacking the weak f7 square
This move prevents me from playing Ng5, that would also attack f7.
Moving my king into safety!
I met this move, and my first thought was that d5 will follow, so:
in case of d5, I move my bishop to b3 still attacking Black's kingside, and also protecting my pawn on e4.
I didn't expect this. I expected that tawba will develop his minor pieces first.
I continued with developing my knight to c3, attacking the d5 square.
I think it was a simple developing move, as the f6 square is occupied by Black's queen (but in my opinion it is more suitable for the knight).
I brought my bishop to a good place, as f4 and g5 squares are attacked by black pieces.

I didn't also expect this. A piece is moved 2 times-and look at my pieces and at Black ones. I have developed my minor pieces, but look at the Black bishops and the Black knight on b8 standing on their standard squares, and not even Black rooks play...
As I am ready with developing my pieces, I can open up some files.
Preparing kingside castling...
But he will not castle for some time.
More exchange option.
I chose exchanging because I can make my rook on f1 play after 11.f4
Black completes the exchange.
